          <h2 class="details-title">Ajanta and Ellora Caves</h2>
          <p>
            Nestled in the heart of Maharashtra near Aurangabad, the Ajanta and Ellora Caves stand as monumental
            testaments to India’s rich cultural and artistic heritage. These UNESCO World Heritage Sites attract
            thousands of visitors every year, offering a fascinating glimpse into ancient craftsmanship, spirituality,
            and history.
          </p>
          <h5>A Glimpse into the Ajanta Caves</h5>
          <p>The Ajanta Caves, carved between the 2nd century BCE and the 6th century CE, consist of 30 rock-cut caves.
            These caves are renowned for their exquisite murals, intricate carvings, and remarkable sculptures that
            depict the life of Buddha and various Jataka tales.</p>
          <h6>
            Highlights of Ajanta Caves:
          </h6>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Mural Art</strong>: The murals here are a blend of vibrant colors and intricate detailing, narrating stories of
              compassion and spirituality.</li>
            <li><strong>Architectural Marvel</strong>: The chaityas (prayer halls) and viharas (monastic halls) demonstrate the
              brilliance of ancient engineering and design.</li>
            <li><strong>Cave 1 and Cave 2</strong>: These are particularly famous for their iconic paintings, including the Bodhisattva
              Padmapani and Avalokiteshvara.</li>
          </ol>
