              <h2>The Magnificence of Ellora Caves</h2>
              <p>Located about 100 kilometers from Ajanta, the Ellora Caves date back to 600–1000 CE and showcase an
                extraordinary mix of Buddhist, Hindu, and Jain traditions. With 34 caves carved out of basalt rock, Ellora
                is a symbol of religious harmony and artistic excellence.</p>
              <h6>
                Highlights of Ajanta Caves:
              </h6>
              <ol>
                <li><strong>Kailasa Temple (Cave 16)</strong>: A masterpiece dedicated to Lord Shiva, this monolithic temple is the largest
                  of its kind, carved entirely out of a single rock.</li>
                <li><strong>Hindu, Buddhist, and Jain Caves</strong>: The caves reflect diverse religious beliefs, with intricate carvings of
                  deities, mythological tales, and spiritual symbolism.</li>
                <li><strong>Cave 10 (Vishwakarma Cave)</strong>: Known as the Carpenter’s Cave, it features a grand stupa and is famed for
                  its acoustic design.</li>
              </ol>
              <h6>Tips for Visitors</h6>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Best Time to Visit</strong>: November to March, when the weather is pleasant.</li>
                <li><strong>Entry Fee</strong>: INR 40 for Indians, INR 600 for foreign nationals (subject to change).</li>
                <li><strong>Don’t Miss</strong>: Guided tours to understand the history and symbolism of the caves.</li>
